	        <div class="contentwrap">
	            <h1 class="centertext"><i>White Noise</i> Music Analysis</h1>
	                <p><span class="song">Mass Destruction</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Faithless</span></p>
	                <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     With its upbeat rhythm, the song Mass Destruction almost perfectly mimics a style of writing introduced by Delilio in <i>White Noise</i>. The ability of both Faithless's song and Delilo's writing to explore unnerving ideas with an almost cheerful way is awe-inspiring. The need to not only listen to Mass Destruction several times, but also read the lyrics to fully understand the subject of the song has an uncanny resemblance to Delilo's usage of lists to include a seemingly unrelated and usually saddening idea within a group of items. Delilo writes, “New sounds, a different flight path, a sense of being encased in a solid tubing and not some polyurethane wrap. The smoking sign went on, an international hand with a cigarette. Stewardesses appeared with scented towelettes for cleaning blood and vomit” (91). Even though Delilo writes about several objects to provide imagery for the reader, his list uses obscure and insignificant items like the smoking sign turning on to distract the reader from the idea that the entire plane almost crashed, making the whole event seem somehow discounted. Parallel to this, Faithless sings, “My dad came into my, room holding his hat, I knew he was leaving, He sat on my bed told me some facts, son. I have a duty, calling on me. You and your sister be brave my little soldier. And don't forget all I told ya. Your the mister of the house now remember this.” Even though he sings about a father going to war, leaving a small child as the man of the house, the encompassing of the lyrics in an upbeat, fast-tempo song, makes the entire message seem a lot lighter.</p>
                        <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/massdestruction.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                        </audio>	
                <hr class="seperator" />
                    <p><span class="song">Dust in the Wind</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Kansas</span></p>
	                <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     Acoustics and pitch perfects vocals symbolize Kansas. In their song Dust in the Wind, the analyzation of death, the fact that there can be no prolonging it, regardless of possessions and social class, shows a similar level of analysis practiced by Murray throughout the book. In the supermarket, Murray says, “Everything is concealed in symbolism, hidden by veils of mystery and layers of cultural material. But it is psychic data, absolutely. The large doors slide open, they close unbidden. Energy waves, incident radiation. All the letters and numbers are here, all the colors of the spectrum, all voices and sounds, all the code words and ceremonial phrases” (37). A study of a supermarket shows Murrays ability to take a complex object and break it down to its core and simplest form, similar to what Kansas does in Dust in the Wind. </p>
                        <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/dustinthewind.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                        </audio>
                <hr class="seperator" />
                    <p><span class="song">It Hasn't Been Long Enough</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Eric Hutchinson</span></p>
	                <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     An extremely skillful musician Eric Hutchinson relies primarily on his ability to attune the sounds of the piano to match the tone of any of his songs. Similar to Delilo’s writings, Hutchinson can portray terrible events in a not as terrible way. Hutchinson sings, “It hasn't been long enough to even begin to think it's alright I'm only concerned with the way we end up.” In the context of <i>White Noise</i>, the quote applies perfectly to the idea of the fear of death found throughout the book. Jack says in <i>White Noise</i>, “That little breath of Nyodene has planted a death in my body. It is now official, according to the computer. I’ve got death inside me. It’s just a question of whether or not I can outlive it” (144). A paraphrase of Jack’s concern would be almost equivalent to Hutchinson’s lyrics.  </p>
                    <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/ithasntbeenlongenough.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                    </audio>
                    
                <hr class="seperator" />
                <p><span class="song">Pain</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Jimmy Eat World</span></p>
	            <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     Babette is at first seen as a loving and trustworthy mother and wife. Throughout the story, she becomes less and less so.  The discovery of Babette taking Dylar and the fact that she had an affair to get it shows the intensity of the feelings she had towards death. In Jimmy Eat World’s Pain, he sings of an object that takes his pain away. This same concept can easily be fitted to Babette. The use of Dylar takes away the intense emotions brought on her by her fear of death. Seeking the help of an untested medical drug instead of a doctor or the advice of her husband shows the intense loneliness brought on her by her fear of death as well as the seriousness of her condition to her. </p>
                    
                    <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/pain.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                    </audio>
                
                <hr class="seperator" />
                    <p><span class="song">Bret, You've Got It Going On</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Flight of the Conchords</span></p>
	                <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     While it would no doubt be a little more than slightly uncomfortable to have this song played for you, the relationship between the singer Jermaine and Bret, his friend he is trying to cheer up, is very similar to the relationship between Murray and Jack. Murray at times can be very weird, exemplified when Murray has an interesting impulse to smell items residing in the Gladney’s cart. Delilo writes, “He took a twin roll of paper towels out of her cart and smelled it” (37). Regardless, as eccentric as Murray seems, he always provide Jack with advice when needed, similar to how Jermaine plays Bret a song to make him feel better.</p>
                        <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/bretyouvegotitgoingon.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                        </audio>
                    
                <hr class="seperator" />
                    <p><span class="song">Nobody Home</span> <span class="by">by </span><span class="artist">Pink Floyd</span></p>
	                <p class="description">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     A sense of randomness is apparent throughout <i>White Noise</i>. This is seen clearly when Denise tries to extract a confession from Babette about taking Dylar. A conversation that starts with a topic of an underground and experimental medical drug ends with Bolivians. Even though the beginning point of the conversation vastly differs from the end point, Delilo does not simply jump from one topic to another, he uses the flow of conversation to direct it to its final point. An example of this is when there is an ongoing conversation in the Gladney’s car, Babette asks, “Are you tellin me a two-hump camel stores food in one hump and water in the other?” and Heinrich responds, The important thing about camels, is that camel meat is considered a delicacy.” To which Denise responds, “I thought that was alligator meat” (81). Delilo does not jump from a discussion of camels to a discussion of alligator meat but rather uses the natural flow of conversation to make the randomness seem less obtrusive. This same concept is also found in Pink Floyd’s song, Nobody Home. Roger Waters sings, “I got thirteen channels of shit on the TV to choose from” and continues on by singing, “I’ve got electric light.” Waters and Delilo both rapidly change from topic to topic to induce a sense of randomness, but both authors keep some sort of connection between them. </p>
                        <audio id="player" class="player" src="mediaplayer/media/nobodyhome.mp3" type="audio/mp3" controls="controls">		
                        </audio>
